React Native is like React, but it uses native
components instead of web components as building blocks.
So to understand the basic structure of a React Native
app, you need to understand some of the basic React
concepts, like JSX, components, state, and props. 
If you already know React, you still need to learn
some React Native specific stuff, like the native
components. This tutorial is aimed at all 
audiences, whether you have React experience or not.

React Native is an open-source framework developed by Meta in 2015 
that enables developers to build mobile applications for iOS and Android
 using JavaScript and React. It connects to the same principle as 
 React for web development—using a declarative UI paradigm—but instead 
 of rendering to the DOM, it renders directly to native mobile components.

 Today, React Native powers apps used by millions of people worldwide. 
 Notable companies using React Native include:

Instagram
Microsoft (Xbox, Office, Outlook, Teams)
Amazon (Shopping, Alexa, Photos)
Shopify
PlayStation App
Discord
Codecademy Go (our learning app!)

React Native renders use native UI components from each platform 
rather than web views. This gives apps the look, feel, and performance
 of native apps while still using JavaScript for the business logic.

 In React for the web, components render to HTML elements in the browser’s DOM.
  React Native instead renders genuine native UI components—a <View> becomes an 
  UIView on iOS or android.view on Android. This direct mapping results in truly 
  native interfaces.

React Native also replaces CSS with JavaScript-based styling, which resembles CSS 
syntax but is interpreted by the native rendering engine.

learn once, write anywhere”

Native components also vary visually across platforms because React Native maps 
to the platform’s own UI elements. Text inputs may appear with rounded corners on 
iOS, but are underlined on Android, and date pickers render them as wheels on iOS 
and calendar popups on Android. These differences are intentional and enhance the 
user experience by aligning with platform conventions.

So what exactly is Expo? At its core, Expo builds on React Native. 
Every Expo project is a React Native project with enhanced tooling and libraries.
 Expo simplifies the developer experience while React Native handles the actual 
 rendering to native components.

 The framework’s capabilities are proven by companies like Bluesky, 
 StubHub, and Coinbase, who use Expo to ship successful apps at scale.

 React Native provides special components designed for mobile interfaces. 
 Components like <View> and <Text> (which we’ll explore shortly) map directly to 
 platform-specific UI elements. For example, a <View> becomes a UIView on iOS or an
  android.view.View on Android. These mappings allow us to write JavaScript while still 
  creating genuine native interfaces.

What is <View>?
View is a wrapper for other UI elements, allowing us to organize content and
layouts effectively. This component functions similar to div for html development, butview is used  to 
structure the layout of a mobile screen, and doe snot have defualt styling or text
rendering capabilites. it is a container. 

what is <Text>?
The <Text> cmponent is reacts native way of rendering text. inreact native, all text
must be wrapped in a <text> component. Here is an example:
import { Text, View } from 'react-native';

export default function TextExample() {
  return (
    <View>
      <Text>
        This is a sentence with <Text>nested text</Text>.
      </Text>
    </View>
  );
}

What is <Image>?
The <Image> component displasy images from various soruces such as local asses, network resoruces
or even base64 encoded data. Here is an example:
import { Image, View } from 'react-native';

export default function ImageExample() {
  return (
    <View>
      {/* Local image */}
      <Image
        source={require('./assets/logo.png')}
        style={{ width: 100, height: 100 }}
      />

      {/* Network image */}
      <Image
        source={{ uri: 'https://example.com/image.jpg' }}
        style={{ width: 100, height: 100 }}
      />
    </View>
  );
}

What is <ScrollView>?
<ScrollView> provides scrollable container when content exceed the 
screen size, think of a socila media feed. <View> is more fixed, but <ScrollView> allows users to scroll though long
list, images, or text.

Here is an example:
import { ScrollView, Text, View } from 'react-native';

export default function ScrollViewExample() {
  return (
    <ScrollView>
      <View style={{ height: 900}}>
        <Text>Item 1</Text>
      </View>
      <View style={{ height: 900}}>
        <Text>Item 2</Text>
      </View>
    </ScrollView>
  );
}

